Corinna Shen, an Asian American and Pacific Islander community leader in Rockville, Maryland, is unsure exactly how many times her home has been vandalized since it was first targeted in 2016.\
\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Last September, she discovered footprints on her front door after a series of bangs shook the house while she and her family were eating dinner.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \
Similar incidents at Shen\'92s home, which she believes are hate crimes because other homes in her neighborhood weren\'92t targeted, occurred twice the following month.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \
Hate crimes targeting Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders in Maryland have more than doubled since 2018, according to an April 9 press release from the governor\'92s office.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \
To better address this surge, lawmakers, state leaders and victims of anti-Asian hate say that Maryland\'92s government and law enforcement agencies must improve their reporting of and response to hate crimes.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \
Lawmakers say Maryland\'92s statute \'96 which defines a hate crime as an illegal act \'93motivated either in whole or in substantial part by\'94 prejudice \'96 is strong, but victims and their communities must feel safe reporting incidents for the statute to be effective in addressing hate crimes.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \
Lawmakers updated Maryland\'92s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gcr&section=10-304&enactments=False&archived=False"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 statute}} last year after a white man murdered Black Army lieutenant Richard Collins III on the University of Maryland, College Park campus in 2017.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \
The U.S. Senate on Thursday passed legislation aimed at combating hate crimes, particularly against Asian Americans, which also saw an uptick nationally during the coronavirus pandemic.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 \
Nowadays, Shen generally tries to avoid public places, and she no longer goes on walks after sunset.\cf0 \cb1 \
